Morningstars Analysis

A sound investment process and strong management team underpin Kotak Debt Hybrid Dir Gr's Morningstar Medalist Rating of Gold.
Morningstar Manager Research
Morningstar

Summary

The portfolio maintains a sizable cost advantage over competitors, priced within the cheapest fee quintile among peers.

The strategy's effective investment philosophy supports a High Process Pillar rating. Independent of the rating, analysis of the strategy's portfolio shows it has maintained a significant overweight position in the consumer defensive sector and the utilities sector compared with category peers. The strategys management team earns an Above Average People Pillar rating. The strategy's parent organization earns the firm an Above Average Parent Pillar rating. People Pillar and Parent Pillar ratings for this strategy are indirectly assigned by a Morningstar analyst rather than algorithmically derived. Please see the notes following each pillar section for more details. The details of assigning methods can be found in each pillar section.

by Morningstar Manager Research
Rated on Mar 31, 2025, Published on Mar 31, 2025
Morningstar's evaluation of this fund's process aims to determine how repeatable, consistent, and reliable it is, and whether management maintains a competitive advantage.

Process

High

Kotak Debt Hybrid Fund earns a High Process Pillar rating.

The predominant contributor to the rating is its parent firm's excellent long-term risk-adjusted performance, as shown by the firm's average 10-year Morningstar Rating of 3.5 stars. The parent firm's five-year risk-adjusted success ratio of 66% also influences the rating. The measure indicates the percentage of a firm's funds that have beat their respective category's median return for the period. Their commendable success ratio suggests that the firm does well for investors and that this fund may benefit from that. Noteworthy risk-adjusted performance also contributes to the process, as shown by the fund's five-year alpha calculated relative to the category index, which suggests that the managers have shown skill in their allocation of risk.

This strategy is positioned similarly to Conservative Allocation peers, in terms of its fixed-income to equity breakdown, with a 74.3% to 23.1% fixed-income to equity weighting. Its equity sleeve has a meaningful tilt toward both smaller market-cap and value-oriented stocks compared with category peers. The strategy has three region or sector biases compared to category peers. The portfolio's most meaningful overexposure is to the consumer defensive sector. It also maintains an overweight position in the utilities sector. And finally, the portfolio has a consistent overweight in the consumer cyclical sector.

The portfolio is overweight in utilities and technology relative to the category average by 4.2 and 2.6 percentage points, respectively. The sectors with low exposure compared with category peers are basic materials and industrials, underweight the average by 3.7 and 3.0 percentage points of assets, respectively.

The funds bond allocation maintains lower credit risk as the funds average credit rating is AAA compared with the category averages BB.

by Morningstar Manager Research
Rated on Mar 31, 2025, Published on Apr 28, 2025
Kotak Debt Hybrid Fund earns an Above Average People Pillar rating.

People

Above Average

Abhishek Bisen, the longest-tenured manager on the strategy, provides strong guidance, offering 17 years of listed portfolio management experience. Abhishek Bisen has a listed co-manager. Together, they average 11 years of listed portfolio management experience. As a team, they manage three investment vehicles together.

Note: The People Pillar rating is indirectly assigned by an analyst. The longest-tenured manager of the fund also manages a different product rated by an analyst. Their analyst-assigned People Pillar rating is combined here with the People scores (algorithmic or analyst-assigned) for the funds other managers on a tenure-weighted basis.

by Morningstar Manager Research
Rated on Mar 31, 2025, Published on Apr 28, 2025
Kotak's robust investment culture shines through its extensive analytical capabilities, even amid the departure of key personnel.
Nehal Meshram
Senior Analyst

Parent

Above Average

The newly hired portfolio managers bring considerable expertise, having aligned with Kotak AMCs investment philosophy, and ensuring a smooth transition and contributing to the company's Above Average Parent rating.

Kotak Asset Management Company is a 100% subsidiary of Kotak Mahindra Bank and has consistently grown to become among the largest fund houses in India. It has put in a lot of effort to develop a strong team and robust investment processes. As a result, its funds are managed consistently and have led to strong long-term success ratios, measured by the percentage of funds that have both survived and outperformed peers. The firm had successfully retained key talent until recently when it experienced the departures of two senior portfolio managers on the equity side along with Lakshmi Iyer, who served as the CIO for fixed income, stepping down in November 2022 to head another business within the group. Although the fund house has hired experiences resources, potential workload issues remain a concern, particularly for the fixed-income team.

The remuneration structure ensures that investment teams interests are aligned with investors through business equity ownership and incentives linked to the performance of the strategies. Time frames of up to five years are considered for variable pay, depending on the strategy. Part of the compensation is deferred in the form of an employee stock ownership plan. Moreover, the firm has been encouraging fund ownership among portfolio managers and analysts prior to it being made mandatory by the regulator, which is a testimony of its good practices toward investors.

The AMC has been prudent with new fund launches, instead focusing on existing funds and delivering consistent returns. Unfortunately, the firms expense ratio for regular share classes for a few funds are higher than the category median. Its index funds regular share classes are also priced expensively. The firm could do better on that front.

by Nehal Meshram
Rated on Mar 31, 2025, Published on May 3, 2024
Performance-wise, this share class, with returns reported in Indian Rupee, has demonstrated it is resilient over the long term, with notable returns compared with peers and when adjusted for risk.
Morningstar Manager Research
Morningstar

Performance

The share class outstripped the category index, CRISIL Hybrid 85+15 Conservative Index, with a higher Sharpe ratio, a measure of risk-adjusted return, over the trailing 10-year period. However, these returns were accompanied by additional risk, with a standard deviation of 5.3% compared to the benchmark's 3.6%. Finally, the share class proved itself effective by generating positive alpha, over the same period, against the category group index: a benchmark that encapsulates the performance of the broader asset class.

The fund's long-term absolute return track record is equally convincing. On a 10-year basis, this share class beat the category index on an annualized basis by 2.0 percentage points. It has also beaten its average peer by an annualized 4.5 percentage points, over the same 10-year period.

by Morningstar Manager Research
Published on Apr 28, 2025
By minimizing expenses, investors can maximize their expected returns.

Price

This share class lands in the cheapest quintile of its Morningstar Category. Its attractive fee, paired with the funds People, Process, and Parent Pillars, indicates that this share class can deliver positive alpha against its category benchmark, leading to its Morningstar Medalist Rating of Gold.

by Morningstar Manager Research
Published on Apr 28, 2025

Morningstar evaluates funds based on three key pillars Process, People and Parent. Morningstar also assesses Performance and Price when assigning Medalist Ratings to vehicles. The Medalist Ratings indicate which investments Morningstar believes are likely to outperform a relevant index or peer group average on a risk-adjusted basis over time.

1. Process: What is the funds strategy and does management have a competitive advantage enabling it to execute the process well and consistently over time?

2. People: What is Morningstars assessment of the managers talent, tenure, and resources?

3. Parent: What priorities prevail at the firm? Stewardship or salesmanship?

4. Performance: Is the funds performance pattern logical given its process? Has the fund earned its keep with strong risk-adjusted returns over relevant time periods? It is not a distinct pillar. Rather, Morningstar considers performance within the context of the other pillar assessments it conducts, notably People and Process.

5. Price: Is the fund a good value proposition compared with similar funds sold through similar channels? Morningstar takes fees into account when assigning ratings to vehicles but does not maintain a separate Price Pillar.

The conduct of Morningstars analysts is governed by Morningstars Code of Ethics, Securities Trading and Disclosure Policy, and Morningstar Manager Research Integrity Policy. For information regarding conflicts of interest, please click Compliance & Disclosures

The report may contain a Morningstar Medalist Rating or Pillar Scores that were derived quantitatively and/or quantitatively-driven written analysis (collectively, Quantitatively-Driven Content) generated by a series of statistical models intended to replicate Morningstars analyst output (Analyst-Driven Content). Given the nature of quantitatively driven content, this report may not be fully attributable to one analyst. To learn more about the Morningstar Medalist Rating and accompanying written analysis, please refer to the methodology document.

Sustainability Summary: The Sustainability Summary is autogenerated text produced on investments that have both a Morningstar Sustainability Rating and a Carbon Risk Score, contextualizing various ESG metrics and datapoints proprietary to Morningstar and Sustainalytics.

How do we decide what investments receive a Sustainability Summary?

Morningstar generates quantitatively driven content that covers the Environmental, Social, and Governance (ESG) characteristics for managed investments that have both a Morningstar Sustainability Rating and a Carbon Risk Score, called the Sustainability Strategy Summary. To generate individualized content, the Sustainability Summary requires sufficient data to create its framework of mental models designed to mimic content written by analysts. The Sustainability Strategy Summary uses an algorithm designed to predict the ESG analysis that analysts would produce on the investment product if they covered it.
